      "text": "In March 1973, the British film scholar [[Laura Mulvey]] gave a lecture in the French Department at the University of Wisconsin, which was published two years later in the journal Screen under the title \"Visual Pleasure and Narrative Cinema\" [https://www.amherst.edu/system/files/media/1021/Laura%2520Mulvey,%2520Visual%2520Pleasure.pdf pdf] and has since had a tremendous impact on feminist film theory. Although Mulvey used the phrase male gaze only once, the term became a cipher for the relationship between cinema and patriarchy par excellence."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "f50a7a87f183e153",
      "text": "Mulvey's essay, with its polemical, highly complex language, clearly shows the color of its context of origin in the early seventies. The second feminist wave is at its peak, the dominant Hollywood studio system seems to be coming to its end, and the new French theories are being discussed in leftist reading circles."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "4805951ba5ef0303",
      "text": "These three developments influence the young London film lover. Mulvey and her friends read the Cahiers du Cinema and watch the films of Chantal Akerman, Joyce Wieland and Yvonne Rainer; an alternative feminist cinema that wants to break with the habits of viewing formed by the culture industry. Together with Peter Wollen, Mulvey begins to produce experimental films herself. In particular, she would later describe her curatorial involvement in the \"Women's Event\" at the Edinburgh Film Festival in 1972 as her turning point towards a feminist film exegesis."
